{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487536"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"369"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/369"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.04,0.06,0.14,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"369"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/369"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"369"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87263"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1533"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2137"},{"type":"tags","id":"2380"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"9590"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"524"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is recovering in a surgical ward after sustaining a head injury from falling off his bicycle. Three days after his trauma, he is alert and oriented without headache. He has been eating and drinking normally. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. A urinary catheter is in place with urine output of 260 mL over the last six hours. He is receiving intravenous Hartmann\u0027s solution at 2 L over 24 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 127 mmol/L (137-147)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 3.5 mmol/L (3.5-4.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 104 mmol/L (100-109)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 26 mmol/L (22-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 2.8 mmol/L (2.7-8.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOsmolality 265 mOsm/L (280-300)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine sodium is 400 mmol/L (75-300) on 24-hour collection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous hypertonic saline","Intravenous furosemide","Oral sodium supplements","Intravenous isotonic saline","Fluid restriction over the next 24 hours to 500 mL"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with Syndrome of Inappropriate ADH (SIADH) secondary to head injury. The diagnosis is supported by euvolaemic hypotonic hyponatraemia (low serum sodium and osmolality), inappropriately high urine sodium, and normal renal function in the context of recent head trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction over the next 24 hours to 500 mL\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for SIADH in a clinically stable patient. By restricting fluid intake, the excess water retention is gradually corrected, allowing serum sodium to normalise. This approach is safe and effective, particularly when the hyponatraemia is mild to moderate and the patient is asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe hyponatraemia (sodium \u0026lt;120 mmol/L) or when patients are symptomatic with altered mental status, seizures, or coma. This patient is clinically stable with only mild hyponatraemia, making hypertonic saline inappropriate and potentially dangerous due to the risk of central pontine myelinolysis from rapid correction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for hypervolaemic hyponatraemia, typically seen in heart failure, cirrhosis, or nephrotic syndrome. In SIADH, the patient is euvolaemic, and loop diuretics would be ineffective and potentially harmful by causing further electrolyte disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral sodium supplements\u003C/strong\u003E are occasionally used in chronic hyponatraemia but are not appropriate for acute SIADH. They do not address the underlying pathophysiology of inappropriate water retention and are ineffective in raising serum sodium levels in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous isotonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E would be counterproductive in SIADH. Despite being isotonic relative to normal plasma, in SIADH the retained water leads to a greater drop in serum sodium as the kidney continues to retain water and excrete sodium. This paradoxically worsens the hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fluid restriction is the first-line treatment for SIADH in a clinically stable patient","Head injury is a common cause of SIADH, which presents with euvolaemic hypotonic hyponatraemia","High urine sodium and low serum osmolality are key diagnostic features of SIADH"],"references":["Leonard, J., Garrett, R.E., Salottolo, K. et al. Cerebral salt wasting after traumatic brain injury: a review of the literature. Scand J Trauma Resusc Emerg Med 23, 98 (2015). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13049-015-0180-5","Rajagopal R, Swaminathan G, Nair S, Joseph M. Hyponatremia in Traumatic Brain Injury: A Practical Management Protocol. World Neurosurg. 2017 Dec;108:529-533. doi: 10.1016/j.wneu.2017.09.013. Epub 2017 Sep 9. PMID: 28899834.","Rivkees SA. Differentiating appropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion, inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion and cerebral salt wasting: the common, uncommon, and misnamed. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2008 Aug;20(4):448-52. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0b013e328305e403. PMID: 18622203."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87263"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"369"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87263"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T14:45:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T14:45:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"369"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104877"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"gro